# Prep Research Dossier

## Triage

M2 tightens M1b's graph-authority model into an irreversible ratchet. M1b already introduced CompositionGraph contracts, host projection, and graph-first planner/export paths with legacy compatibility fallbacks. M2 must (a) enumerate all remaining legacy-field callers to place regression guards, (b) trace planner/export code paths to find every point where shader/ref facts are still read from non-graph sources — converting graph-absent from a warned compatibility mode into a hard block, and (c) verify that the existing graph projection and diagnostics surface covers all reference states and contribution-reference lookups required by the done criteria (clip shader, postprocess shader, contribution ref lookup, package-state failures). The root questions are: exactly which code locations still read shader/ref facts from legacy fields rather than the graph, which planner/export paths still treat graph-absent as ok, and whether the graph's referenceStates and diagnostics already cover every package-state failure the done criteria demand.

## Research Areas

1. A1: Produce an exhaustive, categorized audit of every code location that directly reads clip.app.shader, config.app.shaderPostprocess, or raw TimelineShaderSummary[] / TimelineShaderMetadata for shader/ref facts — spanning planner (renderPlanner.ts), export guard (exportGuard.ts), render router (renderRouter.ts), timeline-domain (timeline-domain.ts), UI components (ShaderInspector.tsx, TimelineEditor), and any rendering paths. Categorize each caller by whether it (i) is already behind a graph-present guard and only used in fallback, (ii) reads legacy fields unconditionally, or (iii) is a UI read that may need its own projection path. This inventory is the input for the static/targeted regression checks that M2 requires.
2. A2: Trace planRender (renderPlanner.ts) and scanExportConfig (exportGuard.ts) end-to-end for shader/ref fact consumption. Map every decision point where facts are read from a non-graph source — including scanTimelineShaderExportBlockers, legacyTimelineShaderMetadata, hasTimelineShaderMetadata, projectShaderRefs fallback paths, and any stripSnapshotShaders or getCapabilityRequirements calls that reference snapshot.shaders. For each gap, determine whether M2 can simply remove the fallback and emit a hard blocking diagnostic, or whether the graph projector must first be extended to supply the missing fact. Also identify the graph-absent compatibility warning sites (e.g., legacyGraphCompatibilityWarning, LEGACY_EXPORT_GRAPH_COMPATIBILITY_WARNING_ID) that should be promoted from warning to blocking error.
3. A3: Audit whether the current graph's referenceStates array, CompositionReferenceStateEntry entries, and diagnostics field cover every package-state failure the done criteria require (missing, disabled, duplicate, inactive, invalid, incompatible). Verify that projectCompositionGraph and the referenceResolver produce diagnostics for all 10 reference states through graph-derived state, not just through legacy ContributionIndex lookups. Specifically check: (a) Does the graph diagnostic surface currently emit composition/ diagnostics for disabled-ref, duplicate-ref, inactive-reserved-ref, invalid-package-ref, version-incompatible-ref, settings-error-ref, runtime-error-ref? (b) Are effect/transition contribution reference lookups (resolveEffectTransitionContributionEntry in graphProjector.ts) graph-owned or still using direct ContributionIndex access? (c) What projection or diagnostic gaps exist for the done-criteria test cases: clip shader assignment, timeline postprocess shader assignment, contribution reference lookup, and package-state failures?

## Findings

### A1 (complete)

Exhaustive categorized audit of every code location that directly reads clip.app.shader, config.app.shaderPostprocess, or raw TimelineShaderSummary[] / TimelineShaderMetadata for shader/ref facts.

- 19 distinct call sites across 11 files directly read legacy shader/ref fields or consume TimelineShaderSummary[] / TimelineShaderMetadata from those fields.
- The legacy field readers fall into three clear categories: (i) graph-guarded fallback (7 sites), (ii) unconditional legacy reads (11 sites), (iii) UI reads via timeline-domain helpers (7 sites, overlapping with category-ii).
- Category (i) — Graph-guarded, legacy used only as fallback when CompositionGraph absent: exportGuard.ts::scanTimelineShaderExportBlockers (lines 748–803), exportGuard.ts::hasTimelineShaderMetadata (lines 459–468), exportGuard.ts::legacyGraphCompatibilityWarning (lines 805–823), renderPlanner.ts::diagnoseSnapshotShaderComposition (lines 1101–1217), renderPlanner.ts::legacyGraphCompatibilityWarning (lines 934–959), renderPlanner.ts::graphShaderMaterializerRequirements (lines 879–932), shaderValidation.ts::projectShaderRefs (lines 125–167), shaderValidation.ts::validateShaderComposition (lines 312–328).
- Category (ii) — Unconditional legacy field reads (no graph guard): timeline-reader.ts::snapshot() at lines 534–536 reads clip.app?.shader for each clip, lines 814–816 reads config.app.shaderPostprocess; timeline-domain.ts::getTimelineClipShader (line 333) reads clip.app?.shader; timeline-domain.ts::getTimelinePostprocessShader (line 340) reads config.app?.shaderPostprocess; timeline-domain.ts::isTimelineShaderMetadata (lines 316–330) validates both; timeline-domain.ts::assignTimelineClipShader (lines 377–400) writes to clip.app.shader; timeline-domain.ts::assignTimelinePostprocessShader (lines 402–425) writes to config.app.shaderPostprocess; exportGuard.ts::isTimelineShaderMetadata (lines 719–738) validates both; exportGuard.ts::legacyTimelineShaderMetadata (lines 440–444) reads both; timeline-domain.ts::createSerializedShaderStackEntry (lines 445–458) normalizes raw app values for stack validation.
- Category (iii) — UI reads via getTimelineClipShader/getTimelinePostprocessShader helpers (which read clip.app?.shader and config.app?.shaderPostprocess indirectly): ShaderInspector.tsx line 185, TimelineEditorCore.tsx lines 448–449, PropertiesPanel.tsx line 184, VisualClip.tsx line 488, TimelineRenderer.tsx line 1231. ShaderInspector also writes to both legacy locations (lines 277, 289).
- Tests that directly construct legacy shader fields: clip-local-shader-canary.integration.test.tsx lines 229, 261, 413; postprocess-shader-canary.integration.test.tsx lines 278, 309.
- TimelineShaderSummary type is defined in src/sdk/video/timeline/reader.ts (lines 338–349). It is consumed by renderPlanner.ts (16 references), exportGuard.ts, shaderValidation.ts, graphProjector.ts, patchPreview.ts, timeline-reader.ts, and several test files (15 files total importing the type).
- CompositionGraph-based shader projection already exists in shaderValidation.ts::projectGraphShaderRefs (lines 216–268) which walks graph edges to build TimelineShaderSummary[], and graphProjector.ts includes shader-contribution edges in the projected graph.
- The export guard already has the guard pattern: scanTimelineShaderExportBlockers (lines 748–766) short-circuits to graph-derived facts when compositionGraph is provided and only falls back to clip.app?.shader + config.app?.shaderPostprocess when absent (lines 768–802). Same pattern in hasTimelineShaderMetadata (lines 459–468).
- The renderPlanner has the same guard pattern: diagnoseSnapshotShaderComposition (lines 1101–1173) uses graph when present. The stripSnapshotShaders function (renderPlanner.ts lines 790–801) explicitly strips snapshot.shaders to prevent double-reading when graph is present.
- The timeline-reader is the unconditional legacy reader that must become a projector input only for M2. Its snapshot() function (timeline-reader.ts lines 497–918) currently reads clip.app?.shader and config.app.shaderPostprocess regardless of graph presence, producing TimelineShaderSummary[] as a first-class output field.
- No code in the current codebase wraps existing scanners in graph-shaped objects while keeping them authoritative — the pattern already established is guard-and-fallback.
- Contradiction/risk: timeline-domain.ts shader assignment functions (assignTimelineClipShader, assignTimelinePostprocessShader) still write directly to clip.app.shader / config.app.shaderPostprocess — these are mutation paths that must remain compatible as projector inputs but are NOT part of the current read-authority migration scope per the OUT list.

### A2 (complete)

